the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"Morgan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of Welsh Morcant , traditionally a boy's name. In Britain since the late 1990s the name has become equally popular as a girl's name, perhaps adopted with conscious reference to  King Arthur's  jealous stepsister  Morgan le Fay . Elsewhere in the English-speaking world, especially in North America, where it also enjoys considerable popularity, it is used predominantly for girls."],"variants":[{"name":"Morcant","meanings":["Traditional: composed of an unexplained first element + a second representing the Old Celtic element <i>cant</i> ‘circle; completion’."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Ithel ap Morgan of Glywysing was born in 0675, in Glamorgan, Wales as the son of Morgan Mwynvawr ap Athrwys and Mrs Morgan Mwynvawr. He had at least 5 sons with Gweneddlon verch Braifael of Herefordshire. He lived in Wales in 734 and Eglwysilan, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom in 1901. He died in 0745, at the age of 70."},"et":{"675–0745":"0675–0745","0675–0745":"0675–0745","0690–Female":"0690–Surnud","0680–Female":"0680–Surnud","0709–Male":"0709–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","0705–0775":"0705–0775","0707–Male":"0707–Surnud","0711–Male":"0711–Surnud","0650–0730":"0650–0730","–Female":"Surnud","709":"0709","before 0675":"enne 0675","0709":"0709","0680":"0680","0690":"0690","about 0735":"umbes 0735","0711":"0711","about 0705":"umbes 0705","0730":"0730","0675":"0675","0775":"0775","675":"0675","711":"0711","0650":"0650","0707":"0707","0705":"0705","707":"0707","0745":"0745","after 0730":"pärast 0730","Glywysing gwlad, Wales":"Wales","Istumcolwyn, Montgomery, Wales":"Montgomery, Montgomeryshire, Wales","of , Glywysing gwlad, Wales":"Wales","Wales":"Wales","Glywysing, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"675–0745":"0675–0745","0675–0745":"0675–0745","0690–Female":"0690–Kuollut","0680–Female":"0680–Kuollut","0709–Male":"0709–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","0705–0775":"0705–0775","0707–Male":"0707–Kuollut","0711–Male":"0711–Kuollut","0650–0730":"0650–0730","–Female":"Kuollut","709":"0709","before 0675":"ennen vu